<br>
As for women who have been raped, take it on a case by case basis. I don't honestly know or associate with any guys who don't take sexual rape seriously, but I also know women who throw the term around as callously as anybody. At least one of those women has been raped herself, no less.<br>
<br>
It's not really a question of panicking over offending people. As I said, strictly speaking, it's a correct use of the word. So take it on a case by case basis. If somebody is offended by the use of the word, don't use the word. If it doesn't bother them, go nuts. Language is ever changing... The onus is on them to tell you that they're offended, not the other way around. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=grindel>Grindel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>High Priest of HLS</span><br>  Posts: 1845<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/19/03 2:44 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Misusing the term 'Rape'</span><hr size=1> That's a lot of words that still say 'if I want to use rape it's your fault for being upset by it'.  If that's your argument stick to it please and stop rewriting it; you're wasting a lot of unnecessary effort. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chesse>Chesse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 415<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/19/03 2:47 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Misusing the term 'Rape'</span><hr size=1> I'm also uncomfortable with the use of the word &quot;rape&quot; to describe encounters in EQ. Rape is an act of violent domination, and the victims are left scarred for life. Some of these scars are physical, others are psychological. Use of this word, even in EQ, may bring back incredibly painful memories for some of the people who hear it. I'm all for a rape victim getting the counseling he or she needs to recover from the trauma, but even those who have put the event in the past may be hurt by this casual usage.<br>
<br>
It's easy to say they should get over it. Have you tried getting over it? People are going to say whatever they want, and others are going to be hurt by what they've said. I prefer to minimize my chances of inadvertently reminding someone of something so horrible. <p>Chesse Defenestratrix Shardic, <br>
